04690nam a22007215i 9781501735745DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191992nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017357457 a10.7591/97815017357452doi  a(DE-B1597)534049  a(OCoLC)1129159863  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD6079.2.E85 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a331.4/78/0942201 aCook, Alice Hanson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Most Difficult Revolution :bWomen and Trade Unions /cVal R. Lorwin, Alice Hanson Cook, Arlene K. Daniels. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction and Setting -- tPART I. UNIONS, GOVERNMENT, AND INTERNATIONAL AGENCIES: LAW AND POLICY -- tCHAPTER ONE. Government Policies on Work and Home Lives of Women -- tCHAPTER TWO. Women in Union Structures -- tPART II. Union Functions -- tCHAPTER THREE. Collective Bargaining -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Union Education -- tPART III. Union Issues -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Pay Equity -- tCHAPTER SIX. Vocational Training and Labor Market Policies -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Part-time Work -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Health and Safety in the Workplace -- tCONCLUSION. Amelioration of the Work and Family Conflicts -- tAbbreviations -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver half the women in the United States are now employed outside the home, and the proportions are comparable in many European countries. Yet nowhere has this revolution in the composition of the labor force been followed by the triumph of a more difficult revolution—the struggle for full equality in the rights and roles of women. Building upon research begun by the late Val R. Lorwin and Alice H. Cook, Cook and Arlene Kaplan Daniels survey recent efforts of trade unions in Germany, Austria, Sweden, and Great Britain to ensure equal opportunity in the workplace. In identifying the successes and setbacks of the European experience, the authors consider the implications for change in the agendas of American unions. Cook and Daniels show how unions in the countries studied have promoted women's equality through the channels of internal policy, collective bargaining, and political influence. They provide rich cross-cultural comparisons of patterns of government involvement, the extent of women's participation in the unions, education of women for union leadership, access to vocational training, pay equity, the conditions of part-time work, and workplace health and safety concerns. The Most Difficult Revolution will be a vital resource for comparatists in the fields of women's studies, labor studies, political science, anthropology, sociology, and economics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aWomen labor union memberszEurope. 4aLabor History. 4aWomens Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aDaniels, Arlene K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLorwin, Val R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173574540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501735745423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501735745.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK